    <p>Emil Theodor Kocher was a&Atilde;&sbquo;&Acirc;&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Switzerland">Swiss</a>&Atilde;&sbquo;&Acirc;&nbsp;physician
      and medical researcher who received the 1909&Atilde;&sbquo;&Acirc;&nbsp;<a

        href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine">Nobel
        Prize in Physiology or Medicine</a>&Atilde;&sbquo;&Acirc;&nbsp;for his
      work in the physiology, pathology and surgery of
      the&Atilde;&sbquo;&Acirc;&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thyroid">thyroid</a>.
      Among his many accomplishments are the introduction and promotion of
      aseptic surgery and scientific methods in surgery, specifically
      &Atilde;&cent;&acirc;&euro;&nbsp;&acirc;&euro;&oelig;ing the mortality of
      &Atilde;&sbquo;&Acirc;&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thyroidectomy">thyroidectomies</a>
      &lt; 1% in his operations.</p>
    <p>He was the first Swiss citizen and the first surgeon to ever receive a
      Nobel prize. He was considered a pioneer and leader in the field of
      surgery in his time.<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emil_Theodor_Kocher#cite_note-gautschi2009-3"><sup>[3]</sup></a></p>
    <p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Kocher%27s_forceps&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1">Kocher's
        forceps</a>, a surgical instrument with serrated blades and interlocking
      teeth at the tips used to control bleeding in surgery, is named after
      him.&Atilde;&sbquo;&Acirc;&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emil_Theodor_Kocher#cite_note-4"><sup>[4]</sup></a></p>
